 potential.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.zarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-bar#how-to-open-a-bar-section6-step1","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-add-total-costs-288x288-20200817.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"2","name":"<p>Think about your ideal customer demographics.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Once you know your brand and the type of customer you are selling to, it follows that you would choose a location frequented by your target market.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.zarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-bar#how-to-open-a-bar-section6-step2","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-think-about-your-customer-demographics-288x288-20200818.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"3","name":"<p>Research your competition.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Find out how many bars operate in your area. Too much competition can benefit the customer with competitive pricing, but competition can also be a good thing. A neighborhood with a strong service economy or presence of bars creates a pedestrian culture. You can also take advantage of your competitors bringing customers into the neighborhood.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.zarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-bar#how-to-open-a-bar-section6-step3","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-research-your-competitors-288x288-20200811_2020-08-11-134856_rbwp.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"4","name":"<p>Plan for optimum visibility for your bar.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Some bars struggle with inactivity because their bar is not ideally located, while others prosper in the most unwelcoming areas because they offer a great experience. <\/p>\n<p>While your location and level of service can greatly impact your bar, the general rule is to offer both. Bear in mind that visibility is pos